Here's a MAUI example with compiled bindings:

**XAML:**
```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             xmlns:vm="clr-namespace:YourApp.ViewModels"
             x:Class="YourApp.ProductsPage"
             x:DataType="vm:ProductsViewModel">

    <CollectionView ItemsSource="{Binding Products}"
                    ItemsLayout="VerticalList">
        <CollectionView.ItemTemplate>
            <DataTemplate x:DataType="vm:Product">
                <HorizontalStackLayout Padding="10" Spacing="12">
                    <Label Text="{Binding Name}" FontSize="16" />
                    <Label Text="{Binding Price, StringFormat='{0:C}'}"
                           FontSize="14" TextColor="Gray" />
                </HorizontalStackLayout>
            </DataTemplate>
        </CollectionView.ItemTemplate>
    </CollectionView>
</ContentPage>
```

**ViewModel:**
```csharp
using System.Collections.ObjectModel;
using CommunityToolkit.Mvvm.ComponentModel;

namespace YourApp.ViewModels;

public partial class Product : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty] string name = string.Empty;
    [ObservableProperty] decimal price;
}

public partial class ProductsViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    public ObservableCollection<Product> Products { get; } = new()
    {
        new() { Name = "Widget", Price = 9.99m },
        new() { Name = "Gadget", Price = 24.50m }
    };
}
```

Key points:
- **`x:DataType`** on the page targets the ViewModel; on the `DataTemplate` it targets `Product` — this enables **compiled bindings** (compile-time checked, faster).
- `CollectionView` scrolls vertically by default; `ItemsLayout="VerticalList"` is explicit but optional.
- `StringFormat='{0:C}'` formats the price as currency.
